  "projectDescription": "process document. you find homeenergycenter at C:\\Users\\AlexVinckier\\Dropbox (Personal)\\Python\\HomeEnergyCenter\\HomeEnergyCenter",
  "workplanContent": "# Workplan\n\n\u003C!-- Generated by ClaudeContextGenerator \u2014 review and adjust before creating YouTrack tickets --\u003E\n\n**Total estimated time:** ~18.5 days\n\n---\n\n## 1. Inspect HomeEnergyCenter and Document Conventions\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 0.5d\n\nRead the existing HomeEnergyCenter project at the specified Dropbox path and document the exact conventions in a \u0060CONVENTIONS.md\u0060 file committed to the new repo. Record: dependency manager and lockfile format, directory layout (src vs flat, test placement, module naming), logging setup (handlers, formatters, destinations, level config), \u0060.env\u0060 loading pattern and config module structure, systemd unit field values (User, WorkingDirectory, EnvironmentFile, restart policy, naming scheme), and \u0060tailscale serve\u0060 flags and MagicDNS hostname scheme. This file becomes the reference for every subsequent task and must be reviewed before any scaffolding is written.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Answer Open Questions and Confirm Prerequisites\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 2h\n\nWork through the open-questions list in the CLAUDE.md with the project owner before writing any code. Record confirmed answers in a \u0060decisions.md\u0060 file: Pi path to the project, fiscal year start month, folder label format, quarter date field, Drive root folder ID, local PDF backup preference, Billtobox mailbox and sender addresses, preferred send transport, Billtobox vs Banqup account status, number and types of mailboxes, and polling schedule. This task blocks the systemd and config tasks. Doccle credentials are out of scope for now and will be tracked separately.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Scaffold Project Structure Matching HomeEnergyCenter\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 0.5d\n\nCreate the new project directory with the same layout, dependency manager, and tooling as HomeEnergyCenter (venv\u002Bpip/pip-tools/poetry/uv \u2014 whichever was documented in task 1). Initialise the repo, add \u0060.gitignore\u0060 (ensuring \u0060.env\u0060, token files, \u0060*.db\u0060, and the PDF cache dir are excluded), create \u0060pyproject.toml\u0060 or equivalent, and add an empty \u0060README.md\u0060. Produce the same directory skeleton (e.g. \u0060src/billtobox_agent/\u0060, \u0060tests/\u0060, \u0060scripts/\u0060) as the energy project. No application code yet \u2014 only the project skeleton and CI-ready dependency file.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Implement Configuration and Secrets Loading\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 0.5d\n\nCreate a \u0060config.py\u0060 (or equivalent module matching HomeEnergyCenter\u0027s naming) that loads all keys listed in the CLAUDE.md configuration section from an \u0060.env\u0060 file using the same library and pattern as the energy project. Provide typed accessors or a dataclass for every key, with defaults where specified (\u0060CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD=0.85\u0060, \u0060FISCAL_YEAR_START_MONTH=1\u0060, \u0060QUARTER_DATE_FIELD=invoice_date\u0060, \u0060FY_LABEL_PREFIX=\u0022\u0022\u0060). Include a startup validation function that raises a clear error if any required key is missing. Add an \u0060.env.example\u0060 file listing all keys with placeholder values. No secrets are committed. Depends on tasks 1 and 2.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Implement SQLite Schema Creation and Migrations\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 0.5d\n\nCreate the SQLite initialisation module that opens the database in WAL mode and creates the \u0060invoices\u0060 and \u0060runs\u0060 tables exactly as specified in the schema section. Include a lightweight migration mechanism (version table \u002B numbered migration scripts, or Alembic \u2014 match whatever pattern HomeEnergyCenter uses; if it uses none, use a simple version table). Write integration tests that create a fresh in-memory database, assert all columns and constraints exist, and verify WAL mode is active. The \u0060content_hash\u0060 unique constraint must be tested explicitly. Depends on task 4.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Implement Accounting Quarter Logic\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 0.5d\n\nImplement the pure function \u0060period_for(invoice_date: date, fy_start_month: int = 1, fy_label_prefix: str = \u0022\u0022) -\u003E tuple[str, str]\u0060 in an isolated module with no I/O dependencies. Cover calendar-year quarters (Jan\u2013Mar = Q1 \u2026 Oct\u2013Dec = Q4) and fiscal-year offset quarters (e.g. \u0060FISCAL_YEAR_START_MONTH=4\u0060 makes Apr = Q1 start and Jan\u2013Mar = Q4 of prior FY label). Write thorough unit tests covering: every month of a calendar year, every month of a non-January fiscal year, boundary months, the FY label rollover at year boundaries, and the prefix variants (\u0060\u0022\u0022\u0060 \u2192 \u0060\u00222026\u0022\u0060, \u0060\u0022FY\u0022\u0060 \u2192 \u0060\u0022FY2026\u0022\u0060). This function must pass all tests before it is called from any other module. Depends on task 3.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Implement Logging Setup Matching HomeEnergyCenter\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 2h\n\nAdd the logging configuration module using exactly the same handler types, formatters, destinations, and level-configuration approach as HomeEnergyCenter. Wire it into the application entry points for both the worker and the dashboard. Confirm that structured log output (timestamps, level, module name) is consistent with the energy project. Add a brief smoke-test that instantiates the logger and verifies no uncaught exceptions at startup. Depends on task 3.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Implement Gmail Fetch (Read-Only)\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 1d\n\nImplement the Gmail connector module that performs OAuth 2.0 authentication with \u0060gmail.readonly\u0060 scope, stores and auto-refreshes the token at the path configured in \u0060GOOGLE_TOKEN_PATH\u0060, and executes the search query specified in the CLAUDE.md (\u0060has:attachment filename:pdf (invoice OR factuur OR rekening OR BTW)\u0060). Walk \u0060payload.parts\u0060 to locate PDF attachments and call \u0060users.messages.attachments.get\u0060 to retrieve bytes. Return a list of message-ref objects and raw PDF bytes. Record the last-seen message timestamp as a watermark in SQLite so reruns only fetch new messages. Write integration tests against a mocked Google API client that verify deduplication by \u0060source_message_id\u0060. Depends on tasks 4 and 5.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Implement Outlook/Graph Fetch (Read-Only)\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 1d\n\nImplement the Outlook connector module using MSAL for OAuth 2.0 with \u0060Mail.Read\u0060 scope, storing and auto-refreshing the token at \u0060MS_TOKEN_PATH\u0060. Filter messages with \u0060hasAttachments eq true\u0060 plus keyword search, retrieve \u0060fileAttachment.contentBytes\u0060 (base64-decode to bytes), and return message refs and PDF bytes in the same shape as the Gmail connector. Apply the same watermark-and-deduplication pattern as task 8. Use \u0060msal\u0060 plus plain \u0060requests\u0060 (or \u0060msgraph-sdk\u0060 \u2014 prefer whichever has lower dependency overhead). Write integration tests against a mocked Graph client. Depends on tasks 4 and 5.\n\n---\n\n## 10. Implement Doccle Stub\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 2h\n\nCreate a \u0060doccle.py\u0060 connector module that exposes the same interface as the Gmail and Outlook connectors but raises \u0060NotImplementedError\u0060 for every method. Mark every stub with a \u0060# TODO: confirm Doccle API\u0060 comment. Add a guard in the worker that skips Doccle when \u0060doccle\u0060 is not in \u0060POLLING_SOURCES\u0060 or when the stub is detected. Include a single unit test that asserts the \u0060NotImplementedError\u0060 is raised and that the module exists at the expected import path. Depends on task 3.\n\n---\n\n## 11. Implement Pre-Filter Heuristics\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 2h\n\nImplement a \u0060prefilter(message_ref, pdf_bytes) -\u003E bool\u0060 function that applies cheap, model-free heuristics before any API call: sender domain allowlist/blocklist (configurable), subject keyword matching (\u0060invoice\u0060, \u0060factuur\u0060, \u0060rekening\u0060, \u0060BTW\u0060), and presence of valid PDF magic bytes. Write unit tests with sample message refs and PDF byte payloads (including non-PDF data) that confirm the filter correctly accepts and rejects candidates. Depends on tasks 8 and 9.\n\n---\n\n## 12. Implement Content-Hash Deduplication\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 2h\n\nImplement the \u0060check_duplicate(content_hash: str) -\u003E bool\u0060 tool function that computes the SHA-256 hash of PDF bytes and queries the \u0060invoices\u0060 table\u0027s unique \u0060content_hash\u0060 column. Integrate this check into the worker pipeline so that any PDF whose hash already exists in the database is silently skipped without a model call. Write unit tests covering: first-time insert succeeds, re-insert with same hash returns \u0060True\u0060 without inserting, re-insert with different hash returns \u0060False\u0060. Depends on task 5.\n\n---\n\n## 13. Implement Claude Extraction\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 1d\n\nImplement the \u0060extract_invoice(pdf_bytes: bytes) -\u003E dict\u0060 tool function using the \u0060anthropic\u0060 SDK. Send the PDF as a base64 \u0060document\u0060 block in the Messages API, instruct JSON-only output, and parse and validate the response against the extraction schema (\u0060is_invoice\u0060, \u0060confidence\u0060, \u0060vendor\u0060, \u0060invoice_date\u0060, \u0060amount\u0060, \u0060currency\u0060). Apply the \u0060CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD\u0060 gate: items below the threshold are not auto-approved. Implement retry logic (at least one retry on transient API errors). Write unit tests using a mocked Anthropic client that verify schema validation rejects malformed responses and that the confidence gate is applied correctly. Depends on tasks 4 and 6.\n\n---\n\n## 14. Implement Google Drive Quarter-Folder Management\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 1d\n\nImplement \u0060ensure_quarter_folder(invoice_date: date) -\u003E str\u0060 (returns Drive folder ID) using Drive API v3 via \u0060google-api-python-client\u0060. Reuse the Google OAuth credentials from task 8; add \u0060https://www.googleapis.com/auth/drive.file\u0060 scope. The function must: compute \u0060(fy_label, quarter)\u0060 using \u0060period_for\u0060 from task 6, then find-or-create each folder level (\u0060\u003Croot\u003E/\u003Cfy_label\u003E/\u003Cquarter\u003E/\u0060) using \u0060files.list\u0060 with \u0060name\u0060 and \u0060parents\u0060 filters before calling \u0060files.create\u0060. Idempotency is the acceptance criterion: calling the function twice with the same date must return the same folder ID without creating duplicates. Write unit tests with a mocked Drive client that verify the find-before-create logic. Depends on tasks 6 and 8.\n\n---\n\n## 15. Implement PDF Upload to Google Drive\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 1d\n\nImplement \u0060store_pdf_to_drive(pdf_bytes: bytes, fields: dict, folder_id: str) -\u003E tuple[str, str]\u0060 (returns Drive file ID and logical path). Apply the filename template \u0060{source}_{invoice_date}_{amount}.pdf\u0060 with sanitisation rules (strip illegal characters, collapse whitespace, ISO date, dot-decimal amount, \u0060_2\u0060/\u0060_3\u0060 suffix on collision). Use \u0060files.create\u0060 with media upload under \u0060parents=[folder_id]\u0060. After a successful upload, write the \u0060drive_file_id\u0060 and \u0060drive_path\u0060 to the \u0060invoices\u0060 row in SQLite. Write integration tests with a mocked Drive client covering: normal upload, filename collision handling, and SQLite record update. Depends on tasks 5, 12, and 14.\n\n---\n\n## 16. Implement flag_for_review and queue_billtobox_upload Tools\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 2h\n\nImplement \u0060flag_for_review(invoice_id: int, reason: str)\u0060 which sets \u0060status = \u0022reviewed\u0022\u0060 and writes the reason to an \u0060exceptions\u0060 or notes field in SQLite; and \u0060queue_billtobox_upload(invoice_id: int)\u0060 which sets \u0060status = \u0022upload_approved\u0022\u0060 without sending anything. Both are SQLite writes only. Write unit tests that confirm the correct status transitions and that neither function triggers any external I/O. Depends on task 5.\n\n---\n\n## 17. Implement the Phase 1\u20132 Linear Worker Pipeline\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 1d\n\nWire all Phase 1 and Phase 2 components into a linear \u0060run_once()\u0060 function: for each enabled source, fetch new items since the last watermark; pre-filter; compute content hash and deduplicate; call Claude extraction; apply the confidence threshold; call \u0060ensure_quarter_folder\u0060 and \u0060store_pdf_to_drive\u0060 for approved items; call \u0060flag_for_review\u0060 for low-confidence items; update the watermark; write a \u0060runs\u0060 row on completion. This is a straight sequential pipeline, not yet a tool-calling agent loop. Confirm end-to-end execution with a dry-run mode that logs actions without committing Drive uploads or SQLite writes for approved items. Depends on tasks 8\u201316.\n\n---\n\n## 18. Implement Dashboard \u2014 Read-Only Views\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 1.5d\n\nCreate the FastAPI \u002B Jinja2 dashboard app (match HomeEnergyCenter\u0027s web framework patterns). Implement three read-only views: (1) invoice list with columns \u2014 source, vendor, invoice date, amount, currency, confidence, status, Drive link, quarter folder; (2) exceptions queue showing low-confidence items, failed uploads, and items awaiting review; (3) run history showing start/end time, item counts, and error summary. Bind only to localhost. No authentication beyond Tailscale membership. Write smoke tests that assert each route returns HTTP 200 with expected HTML content. Depends on tasks 5 and 17.\n\n---\n\n## 19. Implement Dashboard \u2014 Steering Actions\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 1.5d\n\nAdd POST endpoints and corresponding Jinja2 form actions to the dashboard for: approve/reject an invoice (status transition only); edit extracted fields and re-save (if \u0060invoice_date\u0060 change moves the item to a different quarter, trigger a Drive file move via the Drive API \u0060files.update\u0060 with new parent); re-run Claude extraction on a specific invoice; trigger a manual agent run immediately; and approve the Billtobox email send for selected invoices (sets \u0060status = \u0022upload_approved\u0022\u0060, does not send). All writes go through the worker\u0027s tool functions, not direct SQL in the dashboard layer. Write tests that assert correct status transitions and that the Drive move is triggered only when the quarter changes. Depends on tasks 13, 14, 15, 16, and 18.\n\n---\n\n## 20. Implement Billtobox Email Send\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 1d\n\nImplement \u0060email_to_billtobox(invoice_id: int)\u0060 using SMTP with an app password (\u0060SMTP_HOST\u0060, \u0060SMTP_PORT\u0060, \u0060SMTP_USERNAME\u0060, \u0060SMTP_PASSWORD\u0060). The function must: verify \u0060status == \u0022upload_approved\u0022\u0060 and \u0060uploaded_at IS NULL\u0060 before sending (hard guard, raises if violated); attach the PDF retrieved from Drive; set the subject line to the invoice filename for traceability; send from \u0060BILLTOBOX_SENDER_ADDRESS\u0060 to \u0060BILLTOBOX_MAILBOX_ADDRESS\u0060; and immediately on confirmed send set \u0060status = \u0022uploaded\u0022\u0060 and write \u0060updated_at\u0060. Never send without the human-approval flag; never send the same invoice twice. Write unit tests with a mocked SMTP client that verify both guards, the status update on success, and no send on a second call for the same invoice. Depends on tasks 15 and 16.\n\n---\n\n## 21. Convert Pipeline to Agent Tool-Calling Loop\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 1.5d\n\nRefactor \u0060run_once()\u0060 from task 17 into a tool-calling loop using either the Claude Agent SDK or the Messages API tool-use pattern \u2014 choose whichever has lower dependency overhead relative to HomeEnergyCenter. Register all nine tool functions (\u0060search_mail\u0060, \u0060get_pdf\u0060, \u0060extract_invoice\u0060, \u0060check_duplicate\u0060, \u0060ensure_quarter_folder\u0060, \u0060store_pdf_to_drive\u0060, \u0060queue_billtobox_upload\u0060, \u0060email_to_billtobox\u0060, \u0060flag_for_review\u0060) as callable tools. Implement policy-based auto-approval: high-confidence items from a configurable known-vendor list are approved without human review. Implement self-correction: on a failed Drive upload or download, retry up to a configurable number of times before calling \u0060flag_for_review\u0060. The loop must be fully re-entrant \u2014 a crash and restart must not re-process already-seen content hashes. Depends on tasks 13 and 17.\n\n---\n\n## 22. Create systemd Units\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 0.5d\n\nWrite three systemd unit files matching HomeEnergyCenter\u0027s conventions exactly (\u0060User=\u0060, \u0060WorkingDirectory=\u0060, \u0060EnvironmentFile=\u0060, restart policy, naming scheme): \u0060billtobox-agent.service\u0060 (Type=oneshot, executes one agent cycle), \u0060billtobox-agent.timer\u0060 (\u0060Persistent=true\u0060, schedule driven by a variable rather than hardcoded), and \u0060billtobox-dashboard.service\u0060 (Type=simple, long-lived). The timer schedule and dashboard port must be sourced from the \u0060EnvironmentFile\u0060, not hardcoded in the unit files. Include a \u0060scripts/install-units.sh\u0060 that symlinks the unit files into \u0060/etc/systemd/system/\u0060 and runs \u0060systemctl daemon-reload\u0060. Depends on tasks 17, 19, and 21.\n\n---\n\n## 23. Configure Tailscale Serve for Dashboard\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 2h\n\nConfigure \u0060tailscale serve\u0060 to expose the FastAPI dashboard over HTTPS within the tailnet, matching the MagicDNS hostname scheme and port conventions used by the HomeEnergyCenter service. The dashboard must not bind to any public interface. Document the exact \u0060tailscale serve\u0060 command(s) in \u0060README.md\u0060. Confirm that hitting the MagicDNS hostname from another tailnet device returns the invoice list view. Do not use \u0060tailscale funnel\u0060. Depends on tasks 18 and 22.\n\n---\n\n## 24. End-to-End Integration Test and Smoke-Run\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 1d\n\nExecute a complete end-to-end test on the Raspberry Pi: start the timer manually, confirm the worker fetches at least one real invoice from Gmail or Outlook, extracts fields, uploads to the correct Drive quarter folder, records the Drive file ID in SQLite, and surfaces the invoice in the dashboard. Verify that a low-confidence item appears in the exceptions queue. Test the approve \u2192 \u0060upload_approved\u0060 dashboard action. Verify that \u0060email_to_billtobox\u0060 sends to the Billtobox mailbox only after the approval flag is set. Fix any environment-specific issues (token paths, file permissions, systemd environment loading). Document any deviations from the workplan in \u0060decisions.md\u0060. Depends on all prior tasks.\n\n---\n\n## 25. Write Deployment and Operations README\n\n- [ ] **Estimated time:** 0.5d\n\nWrite a \u0060README.md\u0060 (or extend the existing one) covering: prerequisites, first-time OAuth token acquisition steps for both Google and Microsoft, environment variable reference, how to install and start the systemd units, how to access the dashboard over Tailscale, how to trigger a manual run, how to interpret the exceptions queue, and the Doccle stub status. Include a troubleshooting section for the most likely failure modes (expired tokens, Drive quota, SMTP auth failure). Depends on task 24."
}